\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-490\li518\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin518\itap0\pararsid4738731 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Could I start by asking your name please?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 My name is Turner. Eddie George Turner.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 And your address here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 213 Sumatra Road, West Hampstead, NW6.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 And you're married aren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 I'm married - and a grandfather.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Do you know what year it was you got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. 1940. And on my wedding night - the siren w
ent. My wife and my father went to - the shelters, and I went on my job as a firewatcher. So - that was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 That was in the second world war of course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What year were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 1908. February - 1908.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Where were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
In St Johns Wood. A little turning called Frederick Street, it's called Macalmal Street now. A little charm of a place where - everybody knew each other, knew each other's sorrows - good fortunes - and times of closing time when they come home at night an
d a little ding-dong would go on and everything later.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How many years did you live in the house you were born in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Let me see now, about twenty-one years, twenty-one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So you were there all the way through to the end of the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Right the way through from the early days there. Then - I moved up and lived in St Johns Wood Road. So - mos}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 t of my life I've been in St Jo}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 hn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 s wood, 'til I was married and they came here. My family was born to me
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Only one - only one brother. Brother Bill, older than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 That was quite unusual for those days really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Yes, 'cos - previous to that - well all my uncles and aunties - were one of families of - ten to twelve or even 
fourteen children. See my grandfather, grandfather Turner had five boys, five girls. Every - every boy was a soldier of the Queen except my father. And the girls naturally married, but then - the families born to them were much - well, I suppose all in - 
in all innocence and ignorance it was being curtailed. The family got smaller.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Do you remember how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No, well I don't - I can give you an idea though. Dad was born 1886. And I'm 1908, so - that's twenty-two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How about your mother, was she about the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Mother's about the same age.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What was your father doing, you say he didn't go into the services?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, see - in those days as you know - progress - especially in London hadn't - a
chieved a lot, all the industries were in the Midlands, North Country. London was a place of retreat, apart from dockland, they had work there but when you came to the suburbs - working class relied on the - the happenings in that community like as you kn
o
w the - the splendour of Avenue Road - there were the - domestic - services, daily help, what have you, the - opportunities for - so-called gardeners, grooms, horsemen, 'cos after all we're talking about the days of the horse. Motor cars very few. And - m
o
st men turned to house painting, they had to because there was nothing else. 'Cos we're going to the time when there was Poor Relief you know. The vestry - Monday would have an open kitchen for pease pudding and faggots, that's how the times were. And lit
t
le Tommy down the street, have no boots or shoes, and that would go in to winter. But at a later date - fortunes would smile on that family and he'd take his place with us with his boots and shoes with a nice shine, and things began to progress. Those wer
e the days you know. The days when the lavatory was out back, the wash house, the lavatory, the coal cellars, all out back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How many rooms did you have in your house that you lived in?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 In the house - didn't belong to us. Grandpa lived on - groun
d floor, and there was a annex to the house, and also on that ground floor lived a Mrs Langdon, Mr and Mrs Langdon. Above her was old Granny Luff, no relation, but we called her old Granny Luff. That was on the first floor. And also on the first floor in 
the house proper was Mr and Mrs Flight. And dad and mum, Bill and myself lived on the top floor. Two rooms. Two rooms. The front was a bed sitter, and the other one was a kitchen sitter. Or a kitchen bedroom. That's how we prevailed in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So your mother and father would have one room and you'd have the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
We'd have the other. But - nothing was amiss because - you were born to it. To know that the rich relations or the rich - not relation, the - the rich neighbours around the corner wi
th big houses well of course it was more or less a dream, you'd look in, but - it was a dream to you. 'Cos eventually that dream came true because - mum became - a caretaker in Avenue Road, and in that big old house there - which I consider that - every r
o
om had a - odour, a fragrance of its own, and - there's so much respectability in there, for instance, although the house was empty mother would say, you boys, go quiet - quietly upstairs. There's nobody in the house. And I used to wonder why I was out of
 
breath when I gained the top, had I taken mother too seriously. But it was a palace. Thick carpets - in the old house there. All the stairway would be wooden, which I would scrub as a boy. And as - and that - that was the mode of living. Didn't know any d
ifferent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were you aware of the sort of differences between the different groups in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Well yes, but - as a child I suppose I didn't realize that because - they were - a class on their own, I hate to say - use the word class - of today, 
but they were a class on their own because - if I walked along Avenue Road with friends, and in those days the police patrolled - which you - well, to me it's a mystery where police are today, and if he see - if he saw us boys strolling - for instance say
 
I wanted to go along Avenue Road to go to - into Ells - we - worthy Road and go to Primrose Hill, what are you boys doing up here? Go on home. And we'd be shuttled away. That was - regarded - and that was respected. But of course the time would come - Chr
istmas time and we'd sing carols. And we were received pretty well. Get a rebuff - if we were too early or something like that. But - and of course no peering too, all those - extensive drives - they'd willingly allow us to clear the snow.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Would they pay for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes, and we were generously paid because - bits of silver. Sixpenny piece, I could buy my sweets for a ha'penny or a penny. I'd go to my pictures for a penny. So that sixpenny piece was worth a lot of money. We were happy. And of course 
- in a - all innocence we were youngsters, we hadn't got the cares then. There's no doubt our parents had the cares, but - I had good parents. They didn't make - obstacles.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Do you think your mother and father were conscious of being members of a social group?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No. No. Because - in your own atmosphere you were happy. You had your parties. In fact - the old house there, in Frederick Street, in St Johns Wood there was a sort}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 ing office in Aquill}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 a Place, Post Office Sorting Office, and the - the earli
est Royal Mail motor car, the wheels would be of solid rubber. The tyre would be solid rubber. The roads then were Macadam. Badly kept I suppose because of pot holes here and pot holes there, and that - Royal Mail would chase down - town - St Johns Wood T
e
rrace, down Townsend Road, past the house, and everything would vibrate, and - I can remember the parties. Well it'd be a sort of knees up Mother Brown and dad would hold the mantelpiece, everything would jump. You were happy. Because, as I say - you had 
y
our own atmosphere, now Christmastime, it if was mother's turn - to give the Christmas dinner and the party - and what relations were there, brothers and sisters of mother - or dad, they would return a party on the Sundays to follow, so of course Christma
s
 carried on for quite a little way. And they were happy days; because - you didn't have to stop to listen to radio, there was no radio. And of course television wasn't - was a dream. The piano was there, and you heartily sung - chorus and chorus of - Marg
y. And I had an aunt, not very much older than me but - there was - Auntie Lil, her piano and me. We would sing all the score sheets and everything you know. Great days I - I consider them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was this before or after the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, before
 the first world war. Because - her young man - who actually became a - a sailor, she referred to him as a sailor on the waterfront. And - of course time progressed and - radio came in and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you have many relatives living round St Johns Wood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. Yes - either of the sons - only two of the sons moved out, one went into Surry somewhere, but the rest were just - round - New - New Street which is Newcombe Street now, had two aunties there - one round the corner, Townsend Cottages. And so on
. They were all close by. Because after all that's how - the family knitted. 'Cos the life progressed in that way that - every child at a certain age would - jump classes of the age group, so you knew them all the time. We squabbled, we fought, but we sti
l
l loved each other, 'cos we still played cricket. But - you wouldn't see the girls so much. You wouldn't fraternise with the girls. Boys would play boys games, and sometimes the girls would encourage you to skip because the rope is right across the road n
ow. We said, no, we're not going to skip with you. But you grew up.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What kind of school was it you went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Elementary. You went in at five and you were turfed out at fourteen into the big world - to earn a living. Well they were very -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 It was just round the corner almost?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. In Binehall Road. St Johns Wood. Great times. We'd several achievement for instance - my pet master was a Mr Timms. He wasn't sport minded, but he allowed me to slip over to Lords at tea break, to see how the sc
ore was over there and I'd shoot out - out of school, Wellington Place - Tavenor's Place, sit on the wall, right in line with the bowler at the Nursery End, and I could tell by the old clock there just by W.G. Grace's gates which - the gates wasn't there,
 
that was a tower and a clock there, I'd have a quarter of an hour and rush back and tell the school what the score was. Well first I'd tell my Mr Timms. But he was a great - recalling my memories of school life I loved singing I loved the old ballads of -
 Farewell Manchester, Barbara Ellen, Drink to me Only, and - carol - carols at Christmas time I'd roll out the sheets - to give - yes, to give round, and we sang }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 crucifixion}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 , sang this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 Crucifixion}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
 for the local Wesleyan church. And - in the congregation was - Sir Douglas Hogg, the MP for Marylebone, father of Quinton. And we - we had - well we su}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 r}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 passed ourselves with that singing of - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 Crucifixion}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
. And I could sing it now at this very moment.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was that the chapel choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, no, the school choir. School choir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were you a member of the chapel choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No. No. I was never a choirboy. Brother Bill was. But - you can call me - I was part of the choir because - I would pump the organ. And I'd wear the - the dress -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was that pumped by hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. Pumped the - pumped the air into the organ, because that little church, St Andrews in Henry Street - was the Parish Church of Portland Town within St Johns Wood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 That was Church of England was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Yes, all Church of England. The 
Parish Church of St Johns Wood was in Avenue Road, St Stevens. But a far - in the - late thirties I think - destroyed that. And St Johns Wood chapel then - which is on the - by the roundabout at - St Johns Wood, became the Parish Church. That's how it pro
gressed then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So which one did you go to mainly, to the Wesleyan chapel or the Parish church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No. No. Went to the Parish church, St Stevens. We'd go to our little church - once a fortnight, like Sunday school, we'd all go - to the Parish church, 
St Stevens, and of course - they were the days of Scout - the First Marylebone Scout - I was the Cub, Billy was the Scout, and the bugle bran - bugle band - once a fortnight. Parade the streets, all go to church.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was Billy older than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. T
wo and a half years older than me. Billy was a - not only a brother but a good friend, good friend to me. He took my part in everything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 When you first went to school who took you along, was it him or your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, mother would take me. See p
rior to that you - prior to school days there was the nursery. See, mom would - dad would be working or out of work, mother would be domestic work, and we'd go - on the corner of Barry Hill Road and - Lower William Street, which is now Reginald Street, th
ere was a nursery, and all we toddlers went there. But you know if I smell - rice pudding cooking at home here now my mind will go right back to those nursery days. 'Cos they - you know that was the main diet.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did it cost her anything for that nursery?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes, only a few pence. Oh incidentally - although I went to Barry Hill Road elementary and the cost was nothing, as you know was LCC, London County Council, next to the old church in Henry Street was a school and they were the days of my father wher
e they had to pay a penny a week. And there was some naughty boys in those days because - where they queued outside - before - class session - the teacher would come out and - and - and spy the - this throng there and say, don't want you today and I don't
 want you today, away you go. And he had the power to do that. The naughty ones.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What would happen to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Have to go home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Wasn't there a rule in those days?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No. His word was law.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 I thought if you didn't attend school you could be in trouble?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Ah in my day, not in dad's day. See? And as I say they paid a penny a week. And I said to dad on one occasion, I said, for instance, you had several brothers, why - what was the plight there, 'cos after all pennies was a lot of mo
ney to a big - family. They made a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 concession}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
 there that - a penny would be enable the rest of the family to go. Because that - I'm talking about the days of hardship when - sometimes they had no boots and shoes you know. See nothing of little Tommy Tucker
 sort of - going to school with a bit of bread and jam, that was his breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How about in your house, what kind of things would you have for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 We were lucky. We were lucky. Wintertime mother'd always have a - porrid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 g}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 e, plate of porri
dge, the old fashioned oats. I had a good mother. Very keen for my health. The Saturday bath in the tub, not bathroom. Summertime. Sulphur tablet once a week. Wintertime - any suggestion of a cold, rub my chest with camphorated oil.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did she ever make any of her own medicines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No. No. No. No, mother wasn't that - you see, we're talking about suburb - you're going right to cat - country atmosphere there aren't you. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did she ever make her own bread or things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No. No. I wo
uld go and get the - the loaf. In the Henry Street. Every loaf was weighed you know. And so therefore there was always a tendency there to cut another loaf into portions to add, and I would have to go, Eddie, get a nice - crusty cottage loaf. And of cours
e
 being a regular customer they'd know you. And a little tit-bit would be put on top and a thin-piece of brown paper would be on top of that. As soon as I got outside that little - tasty bit of - makeweight - was lovely. Always tasted very nice. See and of
 
course - continuing a bit - when it comes to food, I can - I've got an early recollection of mother saying to me, Eddie, go round to Mrs Bunion's, that was just round the corner, I'm only a toddler, there's a note there and on this note was - please - a h
earty cabbage, seven pounds of potatoes, and a ha'porth of pot herbs. And mother would say to me, there's sixpence there, and there would be some change.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So it was quite cheap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Mm. Very cheap. Seven pounds of potatoes would - probably tuppence.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about meat, was meat very cheap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, reasonably cheap, yes. 'Cos it - you know, I've been a butcher, my early days I sold rump steak for one and nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 pence a pound. And today - they're asking a pound a pound.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about in the days before the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes, yes. Now for instance look, in mother's day, now you take mother's day. Now mother was born in Marylebone. Big family. In the High Street Marylebone, that' serve people like - or serve the residents of Wimpole Street, H
arley Street, as you know they were - how - well - Barratt's of Wimpole Street, see they were householders then. Where the local tradesmen would}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595  get their price - and the left}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 overs in the shop which I know of which you've got to make money on, you don't wa
nt to throw it away in the waste sack - for soaps and all that, you realize money, now mother in turn, she would go to either the butchers, and that was Konigs in - High Street Marleyboen with a mat bag, six}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 pennyworth of pieces. And - through my experienc
e that when you bring your meat out of the safe in those days it was in an ice safe, everything looks a bit tired and I couldn't present that to a customer, I'd probably have to trim it, and if I can realize a sale, here you are, wrap it up, take it away.
 Mother would get quite - an achievement there for sixpence or whatever it might be, the same they used to buy stale loaves you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 And heat them up again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. See that - that was the mode see, that's - that's - how far the money went in those days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What kind of cooker did you have in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oven. In the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 A gas oven?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No, no, in the hearth. Coal fire. Two ovens each side. So everything was cooked in those ovens there. And of course gas light. We were lucky, gas li
ght Yet of Granny Luff, Mrs Langdon in the annex had - paraffin lamps. And of course the electric light was unheard of as far as we were con}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 c}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 erned, in the - the established homes yes. But not - although our street lamp - our street lighting, oh no, in the 
early days I remember street lighting was gas. And then they converted it into electricity. But the household no, still - that's why in the early days of radio it was a Godsend - to have battery sets, because we hadn't - electric light. See all this plugg
ing in and just switching on, it's so - yes, it's so simple for you, but not in our days. We didn't know about it And - as I say, if you use the lavatory, can be teeming with rain, you had to put a coat on to use the lavatory.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Where would you have baths, would that be in the kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. Yes, in the kitchen. Every house carried a big bath. Water was heated and there you are.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 That would be on Saturday nights?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, always Saturday night. My - my parents - my mother particularly - but dad
 was - dad was the same, when we bathed, when - when we were bathed - straight to bed. No fear of any colds. And that was - regular.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What time at night would you go to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh really - my parents would be in bed by ten, so we children would go e
arlier. Summertime like with the longer day - play in Regents Park, or Primrose Hill - at dusk you'd say well you'd go home and be accepted at that time and wash and go to bed. But never late. And my parents were - had regular habits, not drinkers. Only a
t
 - party, if there was a - party they - well when I say drinkers, dad would get a party going - and refill the glasses and if he thought they were getting merry he'd see sandwiches - were stuffed into 'em, to sober them. Do you know what he'd drink? R. Wh
ites lemon squash. But mum would have an occasional Guinness.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did mother make the family clothes or did she buy them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, I was lucky there. Lucky again. I have a sewing machine now, a Singer sewing machine which was my mother's. The old handle. 
I can always remember as a child - she must have repaired with that. I think she made occasionally a dress for herself, but not for us boys. I can remember my first }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 knickerbockers}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595  suit, with a hard Eton collar. It felt quite good, because - I'd got pockets down the - inside. And I think that was a great joy to any - any young boy to have pockets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So you were one of the lucky ones really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, I was lucky. I was - although we were working class - I was very lucky.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about shoes and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Lucky there again. Although I used to kick 'em out, because I - I couldn't resist a can, let alone anything else. But I was very lucky. In fact - look}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595  this is dad. Dad bought me skat}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 es when I was a boy. And he - the instructions he gave me
 always see that the straps are securely - tied up before you go out skating, and if he was about he'd see that that was so. Very strict. Dad was a good man. With my father, he had no ambition - no ambition for - and I don't think he had a - well he - he 
didn't know how to make a bad friend. Easy going. But mother and I were more - impulsive. For instance - we'd want to go here and there and dad'd say, well look, you go. And we always did go.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Where would you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Like - for instance - we went and
 saw - we'd go down and see shows down the West End. Saw Fred and Adela Stell - Steer in Lady be Good. Went to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 Cenotaph}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
 first opened, when it was first erected we were the - one of the earliest fifty on the queue. When Alcock and Brown after flying the Atlantic, the first men to fly that, we were on the procession, to herald them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So you went out quite a lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, mother and I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did your father ever go out with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. He was more retiring. Now for instance in those days that - in 
waiting for a bus, if a - a small - or so many had congregated there dad would sort of retire more and more whereas mum and I - always looking round to see that nobody was going to take our place. And when we'd get on, look round for dad, he's right back,
 so we said, come on dad, you're on. And he'd say, oh I'll see you. That was dad. You see, infuriate mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did they have many mutual friends or was it mainly your mother's friends who came round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, dad had - no - in coming to the house they w
ould be relations. Because - to put it quite mildly or - or - to - to be honest with the fact, we wasn't - a boozing family. We didn't - go regularly to pubs so therefore you don't bring them back. And regular in their habits of going to bed. Well when we
 had our parties, it would be relations. And of course being so many brothers and sisters there was quite a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 throng}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
. And that's all you could manage. But dad - was a club member, there was a working mans club in St Johns Wood, which dad, in his early years, 
was a member and he became a life member and so on and so on. In fact, the - be - became such a senior person that - in the '39 war, where the shelters were - was erected at - which is now the Parish church, it was then the chapel - dad was shelter marsha
l there, being a senior citizen. And - everybody knew - dad.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You say he did odd jobs before the first war, what did he do after?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. He became a house painter for a big firm - which he would go out and do a country job. Be missing for a fortnig
ht. And then in the thirties, he - the advancement of - of traffic regulations came about, white lines and the painting of - of - of - of lamp signs, black and white. You know, they started painting in the middle of the road with white lines. Dad became a
 painter of - on - Marylebone Council. See, and he saw out his - his working life there and then he retired from there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How old was he when he died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Dad was - seventy - seventy-nine when he died. Good man dad was you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did your mother continue domestic service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes, mother died first though. Mother died fifty-one. Dad died sixty-one. But - mother was - only a - a daily help. But recognised as a thorough good person because that's why the compliments was given to us to care take. See? Which we did do so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 She wouldn't live in when she was caretaker would she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh yes. Yes, she'd live in, look after the house. In Avenue Road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 And she'd just pop round to see you were getting on all right?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh no, we - the whole family were there. Oh yes. The whole family. Oh it's great fun for me. Proper }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 lawn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595  and I could bring on bat and ball and Bill would bowl to me. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How old were you when that happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 See, that's - let me see now -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Would that be after the first world war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No, no. Before. Before. Because I would take out the master's dogs, in my lunch break. You asked there where - when we were caretakers, that could have been the early part of the war years, because I'd just told you there I would take out
 the master's dogs. And at the time - the blinded soldiers - were coming from Flanders and St Dunstan's had erected some bungalows, just by the fork pathway - when you go over Charbot Street Bridge, a fort on the right, the pathway there - and behind used
 to stand a white house which eventually Barbara Hutton bought.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 The film star Barbara Hutton?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. Woolworth - heiress. They built some bungalows there, and housed there were the blinded soldiers, I suppose partly in convalescent. And a little f
urther along, when you come into the park proper, there was a little slip, edge of a field, which the local car}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
man could graze his horses there, but he had to relinquish that. They had - erected some goalposts there. And when I'd enter the park from any e
ntrance, if it was far - over by the zoo, I could hear the whistling and the cries, and I was attracted, and I'd see these boys - taking penalty shots into a - a goal and of course naturally - an orderly you could see. And these lads became so efficient -
 
that the great Arsenal club would send a side there, and of course those men had to be blindfolded to take penalty kicks. And more often than not St Dunstan's would beat them. Now I would know that because every day I'd take out the dogs, and if I heard t
h
e whistles - if there was a game on I'd hear the whistles and the cry, and the dogs and I went one way. Straight there. That was the - sixteen, because - then they became to come out abroad into St Johns Wood. It was nothing to see - four or five of these
 
lads all bunched together, all chatting at the same time, they knew what direction they were going, they were going to Charlie Abardo, an Italian who had a - restaurant - in the old Hendon Street, eggs and chips, whatever it might be. And of course - the 
locals would see them round any obstacle and they were quite happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So they adapted very quickly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, they're - they're - extraordinary.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 When you were caretakers at this house were the people away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, away, yes. See -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How long were they away for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Month. And then of course the domestic - that was the time for the domestic staff to have - take their holidays. The cook - there was a Scotch - Scotch woman, and the other girls would go whatever - what part they cared.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You just did it that once did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh no, several years. Several years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 But you still kept up your own house round the corner?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh yes, round - see that was all right naturally because grandpa was still living there, and there was Mr and Mrs Fl
ight and so on and so on there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Who was the landlord of the place you lived in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 I think - I think the property was either the Aire Estate or the De - Dewaring Estate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did the landlord come round?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. I can remember his name as clear
 as - as it was now. Man named Fairclough. Well respected. I suppose - he was the lord of the manor because there's no doubt because he was asked favours - can't pay this week, we'll pay next week sort of thing you know. But we were - regular, mum - that 
was her code of honour, to pay him right - than ask for anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did he do repairs to the house or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 In a small way, yes. In a small way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about your father, did he do anything round the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Like - dad would naturally paint - in - indoor - interior and everything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about things like helping to do the washing up and cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Oh yes. Yes. That was commonplace. Even for us boys. Now - for instance, you - now you've hit on a note there - I would
 clean the knives and forks, with that powder.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Silv}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 er}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
 type stuff?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes, not - not so much Brasso, but with powder, and I would scrub down the stairs our flights of stairs, all wooden - carpet, nothing so - so - inventive as had a carpet on them. 
For one thing you couldn't afford it and - it was our - just plain wood. In fact I got many a rub in the - you know what young lads are you take every flight at one stride, and I would end up by slamming the front door, and my grandfather would say, you y
oung bugger Eddie. I - I couldn't realize why he was - getting at me for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was he there on his own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Grandpa, yes, yes. The - the children had grown up and - well when I say on his own, there was a young - younger daughter, Nellie, she lived there 
with him, unmarried, but was courting. But of course in the house there were - as you know, there's quite a few people. And we all lived happily there. In fact, all my - our - all our neighbours in that house, we fitted in so well I can - can't remember o
ne harsh word. They were so good.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did the other people have any children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Only one, that was Mr and Mrs Flight, they had a little girl called Bessie.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You wouldn't play with her I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You'd play with boys mainly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. Had to be boys, and she was younger too. 'Cos - the elder child - in a - in a friendly sort of way, you cuff them, oh go away, I don't want you. That was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about the other houses next to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Ah now, for instance -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were there any neighbours children there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes, yes, in the - next door, number 27, mother's - mother's brother lived. 'Cos mother's surname was Sparrow. The oldest brother lived there. There was Johnnie, there was Carrie, there was Alice - Johnnie we - he wa
s nicknamed Chicken, or Flyaway, and that was his nature. You know. On the first floor was Mr and Mrs Ransford. Johnnie was a prisoner of war, John a prisoner of war in the '14 war. Louise - Alfie, Sid, Ethel - Lily, see, quite a family. Mr Ransford was a
 driver of horse and cart for the Metroplitan - Railway, 'cos they delivered their own parcel. There was no -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Rather than the GPO?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. See, all this - forward - well - the workings of - of delivering like today wasn't - wasn't thought of them ye
ars. Even - the local Carmen in those days was Carter Patterson, and apart from that the railway might deliver one or two parcels, dealing with the railway, otherwise nothing. And that - see, it progressed from that. In as much - now talking of the police
.
 On the can rank which ran on the side of Coppins Square, which is the - which is the plot of ground, in - in front of - the St Johns Wood church, which is now the roundabout there was a cab rank there, erected in the days of the horse because it was all 
c
obbles all - all up that side there. But on the end of that cab rank was an ambulance, a police ambulance, some eight foot, ten foot long, two back wheels and a front wheel - canvas and straps and all that, and that was a policeman's job to pick up anybod
y that was hurt, any drowned person - see he hadn't got those ambulances running about in those days. A policeman - collect all that and take them to the hospitals or like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What were the police like in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 They were good, they cuffed you, but they were good.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were you ever told when you were young that if you're naughty I'll call a policeman or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh - you know the attitude of adults in those days don't you? Little boys should be seen and not heard, and tha
t summed up authority of the adults. Our neighbours - in a way, were sort of mind your business, what are you doing down here, go round your own end, sort of thing. Oh lots of that. Quite willing to sort of jump on the - on the junior, but - you got by al
l right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were you ever allowed to talk when grown ups were there, were talking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Only in my turn. Only if encouraged, otherwise - that was the - the attitude, little boys should be seen and not heard. But you'd play amongst yourselves, see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What would your parents say for in stance if somebody hit you, if a child hit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Go back and hit him. And - having brother Bill we did our own - retributions if you like to call it those. Oh Bill and I could take care of ourselves.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Would you ever be punished by your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. One occasion there - we were playing in Regents Park cricket and it was drizzling with rain all the morning. And when we turned - from Townsend Road into our turning mother was looking out the window - you rascals
. We were greeted by the cane when we got upstairs, for playing cricket in the rain all that morning. But - we hid - after taking one or two slaps, but mother's temper cooled and there you are, it was forgiven. But with dad - dad would wear a belt you kno
w, a strap. And if I - if I was guilty of something serious, he'd take of that strap, he says, next time you do that I'll give you this. And he never did. Always threatened, but never did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 But it was your mother who hit you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, mother - I think
 mother's are inclined to sort of clump the children. But only - that's only - stress or whatever it is, mm, of course you're forgiven the next minute, ha'penny, you're given a hapenny go and get sweets.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did they give you much pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes
. I'd get my pennies and tuppences, and further more too - I'd say - its according to you, you'd help - the baker - you'd help the baker, the coal or the milkman. See all milk was delivered by the - it was a - a big round, he'd have the horse and float, o
t
herwise it was the push barrow, the three wheel. And of course the milkman's life in those days was very heavy you know. There was always a chance of picking up - yes, see inasmuch too that - jam jars, you take jam jars to the - the old rag shop and - and
 get money. Ha'penny or a penny, and of course ha'penny and a penny was a lot of money. Go round and buy - load of sweets.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Where would you get these jam jars from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh I don't know, but they were returnable I suppose, see, by my - the rag - rag an
d bone merchant. See when you think, rag and bones, even take bones, if you - had enough in quantity. Yes. Well of course again you take - naturally being a butcher I know about it - John Knights, take all your waste away. Fat - full of maggots. You hadn'
t got refrigeration then, all you had was ice boxes, usually in the floor of the shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was there any tinned meat around in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Not much, corned beef there was. But - when it came to the grocer even the ham was cooked by him, and it's stan
d on it's - it'd be there on its stand and all paste would be in dishes, and he'd scoop it out. Pickles would be in big jars loose, and so on. Even his - sugar and rice would be in sacks in the corner, because he weighed the quantities, that's the old - g
r
ocer's shop. All neatly packed - you could have two sort of counters and a - one - in the shops there'd either be - tins of biscuits, very tempting, mum can we have some of those? On the other side would be - rolls of firewood. The shop would look - very 
span and span with a sprinkle of sawdust down on the floor, but you could always smell the paraffin. 'Cos that was a commodity always wanted. That was nothing out of place, it was accepted. That was the grocers shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You said that your mother and father were both easy to get on with, they'd show you affection you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Mm hm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What kind of things do you think they expected you to be in life, what things did they expect you to hold as important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What, when I went out to work you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Before that, what kind of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No, I'll say this without fear of b}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 ing bumptious, mum and dad were very proud of - both proud of me. And I'll say it, I - outshone my brother. I was very good at sport. In fact - in 1920, the schools 
of Marylebone had - a sports athletic meeting out in Regents Park, and in various age groups there were various dis - distances, and I think I was twelve, so that was twelve and under, I was champion runner of Marylebeone. I've got the trophies to prove i
t
. I was second in the hundred yards, for which I got a silver candlestick, no, silver inkpot, and the two twenty I had a pair of silver candlesticks. I played for London schoolboys when I was thirteen at Stamford Bridge. And I was sport mad - mad - sport 
minded, and my parents would - readily buy me the things concerning that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was your father a keen sportsman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, he - he - as a spectator, but he wasn't a - an athlete, not in that respect. Yes - he was a person who could take care of himself. In 
fact I think he put me on the right road - as a junior I would go in the back yard - with Indian clubs and chest expansion - and when I say that I'd do a thing, it wasn't five minutes wonder. I would go out, and I was proud of that because I can show you 
p
hotographs now. In fact - when I was sixty working down in Barhtolomew Close one of the two of the lads were showing themselves off, and I said, I'll bet you a pound to a penny I've got a figure than you. Pound to a penny. And I stripped to the waist and 
t
hey said, ah Mr Universe. I've always been that way. Proud, want to - achieve at sport, which I have - achieved. Whatever I under - took to do I've enjoyed doing. And I suppose I was - blessed with this that I always had a feeling I wanted to prove whatev
er I done. Without being conceited. I don't want you to throw bouquets at me, it was a self}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
pride that I wanted to do it - to the best of my ability, I - you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Do you think you got that from your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 I think so, yes. I must have - must h
ave done. Must have done. 'Cos mother - my parents were good to me. Very good. And - frankly look this is a little inner thought there - my mother wasn't a spendthrift, and she wasn't frugal, but she had all - helpful in this say, now for instance, we was
 
never encouraged to have suppers at home. There would always - always be the joint the weekend. But - afterwards there'd be no suppers. No, go to bed on an empty stomach. Good for you. In fact that Sunday joint, we'd have it cold on Monday. And there'd st
ill be remnants for Tuesday's - hash. Which is like a stew. Yes. And that was the programme.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about the rest of the week?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh sausage and - steak pudding or something like - but it came - the diet was pretty good though. All plain food. Nothi
ng inventory. Which - which is me now, because - I'm the butcher, and my wife was the cook. Which I married. And it's all - always been plain food. 'Cos my wife - cooked for Refall Tuck's granddaughter. Rapheal Tuck's daughter, Mrs Cohen who lived in - Ha
m
ilton Terrace. Being the butcher - I met her, then progressed from there. But - as I say - with that, mother was frugal, and I've known the unemployment with dad, yet I was always lucky to have a holiday. The scheme of the school, London County Council - 
w
as country holiday. You could pay so much each week into the fund, and you were helped by the LCC, and I went several years - I can remember going to Dorset, Gloucester, one or two places there, by that scheme. And as I say, still - unemployment prevailed
,
 especially in the painting - trade, summer time naturally there was work, but come the winter, no, there's no decorations could be done. What a few decorations interior, so small and so much of the time was unemployed. But I was amazed - at a later date 
w
hat money there was in mum's Post Office. And it wasn't left - by any relations. Not to my knowledge. She just saved. That was her mode of living. Save so much - and spend so much. Yet at the same time I wasn't denied, I was always well dressed. I always 
had a pair of shoes, as far as I can remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did she buy the shoes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, she'd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595  buy them. I always had me comb}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 s, always had me vests. I've already spoken, I had me holidays. Yet we were only working class, but mother would daily go out and work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How many hours a day would she work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Probably go out - leave the house say about half past nine to ten, and return by the time I come back from school. But as I say, I was amazed later - that - when the question of money arose, this is in the t
hirties when mother had her illness - that - I was amazed that mother had accumulated at least five hundred pounds. And that was a fortune. And as I say, with - with that - that was astounding to me. But that was how mother eked out her life. If anybody w
ent without it would be her, not me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Do you remember whether she had less food perhaps at the dinner table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No. But as I say - oh no. When all the fruits came in in the summer time, we'd have all that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How often a week do you think you'd have meat? Would you have it every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. I can give you the routine. From the Sunday's joint - be cold meat on Monday. And the rest of the joint hashed, stewed up - with all the vegetables for Tuesday. Wednesday could be sausage. And - and - I had to go to the butchers and - and get some }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 scrap}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595  o}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 f lamb or steak pieces. In - in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 asmuch, we would have - a haddock for Saturday's tea.
