\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Half past five. Half past five to six. See, when dad came home at night if he was working.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 That's when you'd have the meat course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No, no, no. No. No, dad would - see in those days see the working man - there was plenty of coffee shops about. Where they could do - get a reasonable midday lunch. Ten}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 pence, nine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 pence, ten}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 pence.
 And dad would get it there. But probably come home to a - a fish tea, like a pair of kippers, something - or a bloater, something like - all very reasonably cheap. But food, no there was always food at home. But - not to be greedily ate. Mother'd say, no
, no, you've had enough today. And that's how mother - sort of - eked out life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What would you do at midday, would you have school meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 In the war years see - so many years took up my schools - my school years like. There was food kitchens ever
ywhere, outside the school in Barrow Hill Road there was a food kitchen. You get patties, and - mashed potatoes and this and that. Made a meal. And of course - children wasn't inclined to - stick rigidly to buy food when you - had the money to buy your me
als. It's done today isn't it. You'd buy buns or some sweets or something like that. But - mother would keep an eye on that sort of fashion.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You wouldn't come home for lunch?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, because mother would be - but see there again, if I took out the do
gs - I'd return to Avenue Road, and I'd get a little - tasty little bit like - bit of fish - jam tart, this and that, see, I'd get little nice bit - bits and pieces there. And then you'd have - meat spreads, fish paste - in the summer you'd have - watercr
ess. My father was very fond of watercress.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Would you be abel to pick it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, no, no. No. Bought cheaply - Because - when there }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 
was abundance of growth, vegetat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 ion, like - meaning vegetables - not only the shops but the co}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 ster boys would be coming round with their barrows. Gluts of everything. All go on the market, be - reasonably cheap.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you have a garden of any description?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No, just the back yard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So you didn't grown any vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Or have any livestock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
I had a little - crazy, I pulled up some paying stones to make a little - allotment there, I was growing - mustard and cress sort of thing, just a little phase. Also too I - I - always had an ambition to keep chickens. My neighbours kept chickens but
 not we. Not the Turners. I was so - but I had a rabbit, pet rabbit. I kept a pet rabbit out in - the back yard. In a hutch.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you have any other pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Cat. We'd have a cat. Which I called Tenger. Most deliberate in his - his walk, even when w
e'd - mother dished up Sunday's lunch, I'd look out through the kitchen window onto the dryings, Tango, Tango. He'd come, but he'd just - tango fashion sort of walk. And he'd have exactly the same as we did. Meat and veg.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Where would you eat your meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 In the kitchen. Like the - bedroom kitchen. Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Would you all sleep in the same room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Bill and I would. The kitchen - the bed would be up in a corner, leaving the window, and the table would be here. And - Bill and I would sit against t
he wall - the table would be pulled out just to allow you to go there because - it was very secretive for me because I would pop my fireworks underneath that cushion - which was tied on. - I was forbidden to bring fireworks into the house but I would, and
 I'd hide 'em - underneath those, see and my -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You'd have the bonfire night and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Oh yes, great fun. Especially on the dryings, because - we had - two borders of trees - as well as - ladybirds and caterpillars, the leaves would fa
ll - late autumn and of course you'd go through the man kick them - and that's where you would hide under these heaps, because you had a cotton on any knocker's number from one to seven. And also the great - fun of bonfires, naturally the adults would be 
there as well. But I mean -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What were the dryings again?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was a - was a - plot of land - just - beyond our back yard which faced the houses, that ran parallel with - Townsend Road. Dryings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What was it you said it was named after?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Well
, it - it - there's no doubt it arrived because they were drying lands for - naturally for washing days. But we children all played there. In fact I would relinquish my little section because on our garden wall I'd already chalked up the wickets. I - I us
ed to get told off, young - Eddie - you can't play cricket today, the washing's out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 When was washing day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Well - early part of the week. Early part of the week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did your mother do it at home and then hang it up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, but we wouldn't u
se that because we had our back yard. But those people, with the houses that faced the - this square of ground - they - they would use.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 But your mother did the washing at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. All washing was done at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did she ever have anyone come in to help her round the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No. No. No. No, nothing - no - no extra services - then in those days. In fact, you've heard me talk about Granny Luff, no relation but always referred to as Granny. The extra revenue she got would be through washing
. She'd wash - for people. And in a - small coppers that would come her way and that would be - intake. But I can remember. I would take the stairs there at a - at each flight and I'd hear Granny calling me, Eddie, Eddie. Yes Granny. Will you get me half 
a pint of water? And I can see that jug today. A fat little - blue glass jug with a small neck to it. And I'd go up to the local - Duke of Cumberland - and you go in the bottle parlour, children were allowed in. And - get the - porter for the old girl.

