\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So you really made your own games up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. Yes. Inasmuch too, now for instance I - I - I just surprised my - my in-law and my friends. Because in this house there's footballs and there's tennis balls and there's this and that. I said - it was raining an
d they said well we can't go out grandpa. I said, come on, I'll tell you what to do. I threw a two shillings piece down in the front room there. And I said, now you've got the - Barry, demonstrate, have you ever seen this game? He hadn't I said look - see
 
where I'm standing away from that coin, now you get in line with me on the other side, I'll throw the tennis ball down and hit that coin, and you'll catch it on the rebound. Don't drop it because otherwise that's a penalty. But the idea is to knock that a
s
 far towards me or me towards you. And so you play there too. And if you're on your own that was against the wall. Ricocheting off it. No trouble. What's finer - in the cricket sense to keep on taking the ball without thinking. Yes, it's all games like th
at.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you ever go for many walks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. Now for instance - as a lad, especially - breaks of holiday time - mother would - fill the knapsack, there'd be a mineral bottle full of tea or something like that and sandwiches - and the trek would be th
e same way. Avenue Road to the Swiss - Swiss Cottage, along Finchley Road - to Childs Hill, and when you - that - little pair of - Childs Hill you go into Crooked Lane, on the right side that was all fields. Right down as far as Cricklewood - Midland Stat
ion. Because that Road there was a lane. And where - the Hendon football ground is now - and those houses were all fields. You could go up there and sit in the fields, with the skylarks - 'cos just down -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 These places where you played, you were telling me about sheep being all over the place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Oh Regents Park. Regents Park. Naturally - it was so easy to just fall into Regents Park from where I was living. You took it as a mater of course, that was the - the open space to go to. And all our cricket 
- would be played there. School cricket. And the day of the grass}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6160996\charrsid13067595 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
cutter, or the roller - was only a myth. The grass was determined by the sheep that grazed on it, the length of the grass was determined by the - and naturally you'd have to shoo - shoo the 
flock away so as to play. And if a - if a - the markings were first made there, you'd play there and the block hole would be like a pot hole - until you'd move on. Oh the sheep were there every summer, in fact - I used to get the tea for the shepherd, you
 know, always - helped the shepherd \{BLANK\}
 And all the slip parks - from Charlotte Street to the zoo - they were all grazing grounds. Railinged off, you never used them. Never used them, because - you say never to a boy, that was the - the challenge for you to just seek, and then you do so.

