\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No. No, just the children, the children were shot away. In fact I think - Margaret Powell explains that very well. To get an empty house the adults always shot the children away to Sunday school or
 whatever it might be. But of course - also too the interest there - now for instance there was Baptist church was - away from Protestants. We were greedy children, of course we would attend there because we knew full well there was a treat coming off the
r
e say in a month's time, and the attendance made it - to your benefit that you would be able to go. And - you'd have a tea party in - in the - church hall, and there might be a trip as far as Pinner - or Ruislip, via the old Met. line and they were villag
es then you know. Villages. In fact the show would have its - seasonal tour round there, you - there'd be the - coconut shies and the boats, swing boats and everything else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 This would be in the summer would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Yes. But in St Johns Wood, in
 Charlotte Street there's - now what's the name of the rooms, the Colliet Rooms, oh, it's called the Dewar - it was called the - Dewarden institute. It's called Rooms now. We had all our - winter treats there. And I know - I look up that vast staircase an
d
 I think, I'm going up there. To me that was sheer adventure. A long - not winding but a straight - staircase with a huge wooden rail, I wanted to climb that. Now on that first floor - there was a gigantic hall and it was always divided by - if there was 
a
 big assembly, the partition would come and there it would be. And - we'd have a concert there, and the MCC would get us all going and do you know one of the earliest tunes we would sing there, to get us all going. When the Moon Shines Bright on Charlie C
h
aplin. Have you heard - ever - have you heard the tune? When the moon shines bright on Charlie Chaplin - his shoes are cracking for want of blacking. And his little baggy trousers they want mending, before they send him to the Dardanelles. Imagine can't y
ou.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 He was around even in those days, Charlie Chaplin?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Oh Charlie - because Charlie went to America in the early - before the '14 war. Yes. Charlie did. But any rate - we'd have fun and games there and they were, they were lovely treats because -
 the little snip of the evening would be - after the concert you'd file out and all the parents would be down there on the ground floor to receive you, but you'd have to pass two - wardens they were, one would give you an orange, and the other would give 
you a bag of sweets. And you know what that meant to children. That's how the fun was, that was very delightful.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How often would that happen, once a year or twice a year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh - twice a year. Like in the wintertime. So had the - sort of a thanks g
iving day from Sunday school. And there'd be a Christmas party. And probably in the Easter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
time there'd be a party. And when it came to good weather, now I've had a treat, I don't know if you know St Edmundstows at all. There's the waterworks up there. And now they're building on it. They've reli}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 n}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
quished some of that ground and sort of - come in the market for buying. There were fields, we'd have our parties up there, fun and games on - on those fields. Right adjacent to Primrose Hill. But now its all alter
ed. But as I say I told you about we'd have - the trips to Pinner, Ruislip.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you ever go to the seaside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, no. No. Now I'm glad you mentioned that. Really - especially North West London, I can understand those in South London or East London
, cos naturally they're nearer, might find their way to the seaside, but as far as working class Londoners, they rarely saw the sea. Couldn't afford it. There wasn't that extra money allowed. I was lucky, but I know even to the thirties - school friends I
'd - I'd known all my life had never seen the sea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yet it's only about fifty miles away?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. Yes. See. As you know, there wasn't the money to go to it. When you come - when you stop and think - some of them have got no boots and shoes. But I wil
l say this, there was a pub on every corner. There was those ding-dongs by a certain character at every weekend.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was it quite noisy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Dings-dongs were, yes. Ding-dong. Still you accepted it, I'd sooner hear that than all this - slamming and 
- slamming of - car doors and revving and everything else like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were there any children that your mother or father disapproved of you playing with in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No. No. No. Can't recall a - one instance.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Can you remember whether your parents ever went on holiday anywhere?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Mother did, mother - I don't - I don't recall going away with dad. I can recall going away with mother. We went to Ramsgate. We went to Worthing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What would your father do, just stay at home?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes
, probably if there was a bit of work on, like - house painting or something like that, he wouldn't forego that, he couldn't afford to. And he was a chap - as I say, he was a good person like that but - you couldn't push him out of his stride our dad. He 
had a set way, and there you are, that was him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did he ever take you out on his own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. He'd take me to Lord's cricket ground when I was only a nipper. One little fault I still bear in my mind now - just by the main gate in St Johns Wood Road -
 the footway there - was of yellow tiles. And I can remember dad taking me to Lords and I'm walking - you know how a child is attracted by - tile or - or - yellow colour, I can always remember saying to dad - in my childish way, what was it? He said, dick
ie birds made this one. And I've never forgotten it. Dickie birds made it. Of course it satisfied me see. That's always been in my mind. And that was just - approaching the main gate at Lords.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 How old would you be}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595  when you first went to Lords?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 About six or seven?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Might have been younger than that, because my - my memory can hitch from the age of four, I'll tell you why. With Charlotte Street, no, with Avenue Road Bridge which is Northgate, it's still the same bridge as I've always 
known it, the pattern of the ironwork there is - is like diamond shape. And in '68 I took my grandson down there, he's four, and he's not tall enough to look over the rail He's looking through - the metal work which is diamond shape. And then he found he 
could put his foot - into one of these - designs and lift himself up and just look over the top. It hit my memory, I remember doing that. So I could have been about the same age, about four. Yes. To put my foot in that rail to look over the rail. See?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was W.G. Grace around in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes, he was, yes, no, he was still playing. As you know he was playing up 'til about 1914, '15, early part of the war years. I must have seen him but I can't recall him, 'cos I was always in Lords. Even - as you k
now, sport still prevailed in the '14 war because - nothing like the air raids of - the last war. So sport would go on there, and I - when I gained my commonsense I could stand outside at lunch break, one thirty, and as you know, they iss}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 u}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 ed a pass out, an
d you get a lot of business people there just going for the morning, might think, well I might go back, and you know what you are, expectant, here you are son. Failing that, I knew every well to get over round Cavendish Works. I was always in there every 
night. I chased everybody for their autographs. Everyone.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about football?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Oh football. Dad would make me alternatively either to Stamford Bridge - or - Queens Park Rangers ground at Goldhawk Road. And when I became - a junior able to go on 
me own I'd always go to Chelsea. Eventually I played there as I told you. When I was thirteen I played for London Schoolboys there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Which did you prefer, cricket or football?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Well - I've got to make a choice there, I suppose cricket. I was alway
s considered a bat. And right through from the time - 'til I broke off to - and enjoy the atmosphere of the roaring twenties - up 'til the outbreak of war, of the last war - to the times when I was - when I took up cricket again with my son on the local g
r
een and news got hold of me and I started cricket again, and I'm playing for the suburbs again. Against - I'm playing for Cockfosters - against Barnet and places and naturally I meet the county men, I play with the county men. I always opened. I was alway
s an opening bat. I was a gre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
dy person, could bowl a ball too. In fact Parfitt knows that, I had three seasons with Parfitt, of Middlesex. He'd always stick his pads in the way of a - that good ball.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 He's played for England as well hasn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. See, so I - that's my cricketing days. But - at - the preference would be cricket. Mad on cricket.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you do anything like fishing at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No. Oh no, don't - you mustn't talk to me about fishing, I think that's a lazy pastime. How a pers
on can sit there all day and not get a bite, and if you call that achievement in sport - I don't think that way, no. It's got to be a bat, it's got to be a ball, doesn't matter what size, where you achieve - achieve something. You're the recogniser - and 
when you're extended with the sweat on your brow, and whether you've got the guts to keep on carrying on, that's me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You say your father was more interested in sport as a spectator?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 He'd watch me at sport.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did he ever go to the horseracing or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No, but dad liked a bet. Now I go back to the days of the News Chronicle, which was always the daily paper at home. There's one tipster there at the back there as well as Captain Heath there was a man called Bookworm, gave you t
hree selections. And dad at the weekends when he could afford it say - he might have a four shilling bet, that would be on these three selections. Three cross doubles and a treble. And then when he talked - horseracing it would be on his pet selector, Boo
kworm. But other than that, dad was very content to watch me at sport. That's my son sort of. And I didn't let him down because I always achieved. See?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you ever have a bicycle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 I did. Mother bought me a bike, it was a Raleigh.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How old would you be then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Mm, I hadn't left school. I was a very lucky boy you know. Although cycle then would be about - may - no more than about fifty bob, three pound, that's a lot of money. But there again as I say I was very persuasive. I'd say to mum, 
look, I must have a bike mustn't I? The more I worried her - the more it cinched the idea I was going to get one. I'd dwell onto that bike. In fact - you wouldn't see me ride up kerbs onto a footway. I'd get off and help it down. I treasure that. And I'd 
polish that. And the beauty too of it, you could go out as far as Barnet, St Albans - very little traffic you know. Good fun. They were good days you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about things like fairs or cinemas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 With a fair, as you know, you could always rely o
n Hampstead Heath. There you had Easter, Whitsun, August. Also too Hampstead Heath, all your frogs. Yes, tadpoles and frogs from the old leg of mutton pond, that's the pond -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You'd get them in jam jars?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh yes, oh come out with your jar, go - ti
e your string around and - always get a tiddler in that. Yes. Used to spend a day up Hampstead. We'd either walk up Fitzjohns Avenue, see naturally from Avenue Road - to the Sweiss, Fitzjohns Avenue, and - that white stone pond up the top there, that's on
ly a pond, there's no - nothing in it. You either go to the Vale of Erith or the best pond was the leg of mutton pond. That's the pond just by - if you up - went up Pratts Lane, onto Sandy Gallop where the horses take, that's that pond down there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Why is it called leg of mutton pond?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
The shape of the pond. 'Cos I've read history like since - in my - earlier days of course - to help me with my - writings. The tadpoles would be there, and of course - in those days it was open. Now it's fenced. But i
n those days - the - the banking would be so - that you reach - and of course you get an armful of wet sleeve or something like that, or the - bank would crumble and your foot would be in. So your shoes and socks would. But that was the sport, that was th
e hazards and the sport.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you have any other hobbies like collecting things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Fag pictures. That's all you - cigarettes there - called cigarette cards. Black Cat had the silk. Mainly flags and all that. And then - Pinner Cigarettes - Pinner Ci
garettes came with all the football groups. Various footballers. But other than that no, I had to play games. I wouldn't go to many exhibitions, I hadn't got the time, I was always playing games. Because I - I had always been a promoter of a game. That se
r
ious game, in the middle of the road - a box - and a wicket and coats round it, and eleven a side and all that, and because you're not batting and bowl - either - if you wasn't either batting or bowling, you're inclined after a time to sit on the kerb. I 
was the skipper, stand up. The game had to be serious.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You never got moved on or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You - occasionally, not very often no, because you - you'd spy - a policeman from afar and you naturally you'd - retire.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 We just got dirty didn't you? We just got dirty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Would you be told off for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh yes. Would do that. You know. But - you talk about that, great fun was had - do you know the weather then - we were more fortun
ate with our weather. There was - such a thing called a heat}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
wave which you never experience of today. You had several weeks of this glorious weather now. Really hot. So that - all - the - local council to water the roads with their water carts. A big tank
 on a cart. And at the back - would be a line of pipe which would spray the water, and of course we children would take off our clothes and just paddle behind it. And court ways would be decontaminated, washes of water be - be forced up there and brushed.
 
That was great fun to us children. And of course you - you imagine the child would - if he could he'd get down - if he'd got his boots and shoes on, stand in the water. There's lots doing there. Nothing in your way in the street, the girls would be conten
t
 to play - mothers and fathers over there and - push - mounds or - or - lines of dirt as - that's the house sort of thing. They were quite happy playing and we were. And I'll tell you another little thing too, contentment was so - in - when you played gam
e
s, a son would be invented. For instance - girls would play with a ball - up against a wall and they would sing a tune like - eight o'clock bells are ringing, mother may I go out. My young man is waiting, waiting to take me out. And there's several verses
.
 That - when they played that they would sing. And probably they'd invent one or two little rhymes and add, and that's how it was. Just the same as the old tune, I can - now I've recalled it here that the playing games and of course we wouldn't fraternize
 
with the girls and the ball - is punched where the girls are playing, and they're singing, wallflowers, wallflowers, growing up so high. I'm so embarrassed I collect me ball and run away, see, too embarrassed to linger with the girls. Lots of little thing
s like that, little - when you look back it was great fun you know.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 It's been taken away a lot now by pop music hasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Yes, and there again - instead of you enjoying with it - you just sit and watch it, instead of participating in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you ever have things like kites?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Oh yes. Kites. Hoops. Tops. All manner of type - tops. The big boxer. The big heavy fellow. And the little - round varnish little boxer, pint - pint size and - oh lovely to spin that. And ho}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 o
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 ps. And another thing - thing too. In your junior years there you'd have harness made of wool, which you knitted yourself.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What was that called?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Well I - how it came about I don't know but - in time we're all dong the same, we've got an old - cotton reel, a small
 cotton reel, with three of four tacks surrounding the hole, and you were able to buy coloured wool, rainbow coloured, and with a hairpin from mother - you'd go round there with a thread of this wool and lift it over the tack or onto the tack. In the proc
e
ss of knitting, and the finished job would go down in the hole of the reel. Like a small sausage. That would be the reins. And you acquired such a - such - such a pair of - of - of manufacture, you'd even knit harness. And you're proud of it and so of cou
rse - one lad would be the horse and you'd be the - yes. See all little things like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So you invented all the time really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. See, so there was games in plenty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Would you ever get presents on your birthday and Christmas?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Yes, very lucky. Very lucky.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 It wounds as if you made them all up rather than were given games as such?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What kind of things would you get as presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Well - you'd get your - like the earliest would be your - wooden horse. Get forts. I can al
ways re - remember - little farmyard set. And in my little mind there I'd gallop the - the horse into the stable, you know the little, stables and all things like that. Just the same as the lads are today, I've got a grandson, you give him one of these li
t
tle motor cars, he'll play with that for hours. Sip round here and round there. All in the mind, and that's how you widen it. Oh no, there's plenty of that, because - the Christmas stocking was very much in evidence, full up with nuts and this and that, f
ruit. And you thought of a lot of - Father Christmas coming. And you believe it to a late age too. Great fantasy that was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You say you used to sing, have piano sessions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about during the rest of the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Would you have sing-songs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes, because - we would visit mothers sister at Kilburn. And a younger sister lived with this other sister, my Auntie Lil, not much older than me, and mother would say, Eddie, Auntie Lil to you. 'Cos I'd call her Lil. Yet she wa
s only a - couple of years older than me. Now she could get all the - early sheets of music, rag time - Ma He's Making Eyes at Me, Margie, all your - and I'd stand there with her and - learn it from her, sing it, and when - the rest of the congregation mi
g
ht be - in the dining room or - the kitchen, and when we got 'em into the big hall we'd say listen to this. And if we prompted them to sing I'd whisper to Auntie Lil - come on, give it to 'em, give 'em that. A line of tunes there, and we'd all be singing 
and - Oh Johnnie and - tunes like that, they were love - lovely times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Who played the piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Lil, Auntie Lil. See and I've written about that, Auntie Lil - her piano and me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about your mother and father, did they play an instrument?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No. Nothing like that. We was all fort - always fortunate to have a gram}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
