ent well whatever I've done. Whether there have been failures, whatever it is. 'Cos after all that's life. I've enjoyed what I've - been able to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did the teachers teach you punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. That was very 'course that's the day of the school 
bell ringing, and everybody heard the school bell. That was ring - rung twenty minutes before time. And - even in your earliest memories there, you'd be walking along the street and - another pupil would say, school bell's gone you know. And you'd say, I 
k
now silly, you know, that retort. And when you were - assembled in the - in the playground - after school bell, the whistle would be blown. And you would queue up in your various classes. And on the further command you walk into the school. School assembl
y. Punctuality was everything. I've always been a chap, and I still am, I watch a lot of cricket, I must be at a cricket game before it starts. That's always been me, punctuality.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You think you got it from school do you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, I get it from my mother. In fact I was a chip off her block. Mother and I - thought - we loved the same things. And I was more }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 impulsive}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
 and more persuasive - so I got further into it, and she got further into it. But punctuality's always been my - yet against that, my wife, b
orn in Tiverton - would lose a day in a - I'd say she'd lose a day in a month. Not me. You'd break your neck to - be to time. I said, well it's just that you're - you're - just the opposite. She would. She'd moon around - well she'd lose more than a day i
n a month, she'd lose a day in a week. Now I must work to a schedule in my mind.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did your mother and father show much interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. I wasn't a brilliant scholar, yet I was a good scholar. I was always - third or fourth, sometim
es second in class exams and all that. I'd be brilliant in some and just fail - now for instance - one of my weaknesses was spelling, that's why I was reluctant at first to start writing. But - writing very good. History I love, geography I love. Now for 
i
nstance the little things that come up on telly, I tell my wife exactly - I mean with her she doesn't know the left from the right. In fact - I wrote in the school book down at Tiverton which we've just visited, there's a school book now because there's a
 
museum. My wife always told me - and she's left handed you know, and she was always told by a teacher, Anna, use the hand next to the window, and it's always stuck in her mind. And I've wrote the little - written that little quotation in - in the museum b
ook. But - my wife is hopeless - direction.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did your parents ever visit the school at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. Yes. There would be the school - assembly where - the awards were given out, you know in - in an ordinary way, and - as I say I did achieve because my parents were very - they were proud of me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did they ask you what you were doing at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
What - yes. And when my teacher heard - that I was - at the - plain and simply an errand boy, they were - flabbergasted. And I said, well it's only temporary. But I - somehow I'd like the life somehow, it was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How did you get that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh yes, the - errand boy was wanted and I just took it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So you found it yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. See, and furthermore too I loved meeting people. Love talking 
with people. And as time went on I couldn't see myself - caged in any - office, or anything like that, no. I had to be free. Even now - when the sun shines I must go out and walk. I often take the Heath. My legs let me down sometimes, but - as long as I h
ave some exercise then I - and - when it rains, I'm quite happy, I'm right. And that's how I - conduct myself now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you have any other part time jobs before you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Well only the milkman. Milkman's boy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 When did you do that, on Saturdays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. The weekend, because there wouldn't be much time, not - any other time like - until I got older. Then of course the paper boy and then I'd be - up at the shop at half past six you know. Do the papers before school, that was no - no tro
uble. And I was a - also too I was a lad that if I took a turning - and it was long, I couldn't just walk through that, I had to trot through. That was my - approach to anything like. In fact I'd ride on paper round - get it done.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 When you first took this errand boy job what kind of hours was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 As a junior eight - 'til seven.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Eight in the morning 'til seven at night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Ask me what the wages were.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What were the wages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Ten shillings a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you have half days with that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
The shop would close on a Thursday - but as in butchers shops there's all so much clearing, it could be two o'clock or half past two before you were out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you work Saturday on that as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Saturday was a full day. Your - five day a
 week working which prevails so easily of today was never thought of. Your working week, six days a week. Seven days a week for some. Because little markets was open on - on a Sunday, just for the morning. But Saturday }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 a full day, now butcher}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595  shop, on a Sa
turday was controlled by law - no later than eight o'clock at night but - what time you started in the morning was nobody's business. Five, half past five, six was the latest. On all day. Hot weather. Of course madam wouldn't want the meat 'til late. Beca
use refrigeration - might be a small ice box they might have, otherwise they'd have nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 This was errand boy for a butcher wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Always butchers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you learn anything about the trade?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh yes. Yes, naturally when you're 
in the atmosphere - for instance, from the first - growing of a - ham machine for - fat rendering down for dripping, you'd help to make the sausages, all fascinating stuff. And then of course - you were given a knife to cut a bit of meat - what - might go
 into sausages.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How would you get on with the employers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Oh yes, yes, I got on well - well with employers. 'Cos after all I was obedient. Even under - under stress if - if - something had really upset me, and I was saucy, I'd still work hard. I w
ouldn't sulk as far as work, in fact I'd go all the madder at work. And that was recognised. I was never sacked. And - and of course naturally turning to all this and that you acquire - knowledge, use of knife, and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How long were you there for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
The first job, for a year and a bit. Then I went up to High Street, in a further butchers where there was four boys on bikes. And then - I got older and I went into John Barker's - as a - a learner sort of thing. I stood five years of that. Then I sprout
ed out to seek - second shop}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 man's job, or third shop}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 -}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 man. Not old enough to make first shop}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
man. The time came when I was first shop}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 man and then I become a manager and so on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So you've always been in the butchery trade?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, always been a butcher. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you have any Bank Holidays in the early days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Oh yes, you had every Bank Holiday. You had your East}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 
er, your Whitsun. And your Augus}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 t. Yes, you always had Bank Holidays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were these paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 To us, food}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 wise, yes. But - I don
't - even office workers, I don't think in factories, they worked by the hour there. See where - where they wanted their pound of flesh - they couldn't have it both ways in those days. They only - they gained their money through what they earn - overtime 
and everything else where as you, a weekly paid servant, you work - twice the amount of hours in one week, and wouldn't be paid any extra money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were you ever a member of any trade union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, no. No, I was never - politically minded. All my spare
 time was for sport. Anything to do with sport. As far as politics I wasn't concerned.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, dad, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Or your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Never sort of got involved in political activity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. Mother as far as social life - she belonged to the Ladies Conservative Party. Only for the social life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How often would they meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Once a week. They - they knew - they - they'd make it Abbey Road. There was a church along there and there was a hall there they all met t
here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was she ever a member of something like a mother's union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No, no. No. No movements like that. No movements like that, just to be part of - to enjoy what benefits there was. But - otherwise, no. Just - minded her own business sort of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you ever feel there was a difference between employers and workmen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Oh - well there was you know. You'd call him sir - and you didn't have to challenge any statement he made. And - you'd wait cap in hand at the last moment on a Saturday nig
ht for your wages. And when you come to realize what; chance did you have to buy - groceries or anything at that time of night. So there was no consideration, not by a - the employer. There was all that. But you took it and see that - that's - the only th
ing you knew of. And it wasn't challenged not until later, not until the progress of life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was there much difference between skilled craftsmen and say just general labourers in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. There was. You - you've heard the term - food - food
en headed? Well that was a labourer in those days. He was pudden headed, that's all he's fit for, pick and shovel. This and that. Those with more initiative turned and - acquired a trade, was able to carry out a trade. See, and there was the semi skilled 
l
ike the bakers roundsman or a milk roundsman, that didn't - require a lot of skill, but it requires initiative though doesn't it? And - and of course there wasn't the skills to - to turn to in London. Factories stated waking up with the coming of the moto
r
 car, and they were - that was in a garage form. Radio improved things because radios - manufacturers were - round Great Portland Street area, all round there where the car - car business was see. Otherwise there was just shops. And you're going back to t
he days of the corn chandlers shop because it was the horse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 The corn }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 churn}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Chandler. See? Anything to do with - buy hay there. Seed and whatever it is see. Now that's - oh I don't know, that's gone by the ball now, never seen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You say you didn't do an apprenticeship for the butchers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No, no. Only - well you worked hard doing the labouring - side of it and you acquired as you went along, and you want to do it, you - they gave you confidence to do it, and you - the confidence was retur
ned that you could do it. Because - by seeing naturally you know exactly what's got to be done.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Would you have preferred to do anything else apart from be a butcher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Well no, when I look back no, I - I don't say that I would have liked to have b
een this and I'd like to have been that, 'cos life has been great really. I always have enjoyed good health.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Do you think that full time work changed your attitude to life in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, because full time work was necessary. It was without ques
tion you had to. Full time work - as you know there's - a phrase of today called fringe benefits. You soon acquired that because you know full well your employer - if he - if he stuck strictly to the letter you wouldn't make the profit. There's always fri
n
ge benefits in any trade. And when you're a part of that - I had enough common sense that fringe benefits would help me as well. As a teenager, as a butchers - roundman. Through my fringe benefits, oh I had - my Oxford bags. And I'd have three suits, 'cos
 I was dancing - dancing maniac. And a dance would only cost a shilling. Good class hall.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 I suppose before the first world war you wouldn't be old enough to go dancing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No. See, and dancing hadn't come in as much as that. The Roaring '20's th
at started all that. As you know, Sylvester would start. Yes, Sylvester was born 1900. He was the first one to introduce the new style of dancing, the slow foxtrot. I met him recently. And I always thought it was him and Josephine Bardly invented the slow
 
foxtrot. And I said where did you get the forty-four tempo from? He said, we pinched that from America. And we exploited the new dance. See the tango is the French tango. The blues naturally come from America. And then we invented the quick step. I know q
uite a lot about dancing, and I dance a lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You say you went in for championships?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, star championship.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 When you had your first job did you give money to your mother?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Gave most of it. See we had to give most of it up. Mother saw to that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You still lived at home did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
Yes. You can only have so much. But there again as I say fringe benefits came in this way. When you're a boy on a bike - even the meat skewers, not wooden meat skewers, meat skewers - the households 
where you went to, they - they'd save all them you know and they'd give you them to return them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Going back to your school days, can you remember if you did something that the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. The teacher would - u
p - would walk up and down the class and - as you know, from the front benches there they'd always raise up towards the back of the class so that every - they could see what was going on all right. When there was - an atmosphere of a bit of fun going on a
t
 times - which the teacher would detect, and he'd always carry a - a - a paper pointer. Cardboard sort of thing, he'd rap your knuckles with that. But - anything out and out naughty - would go beyond his - jurisdiction, it would go to headmaster. And the 
severity of what - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 misdemeanour}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
 had taken place - was the difference between you - having the cane across your hands, or your trousers down. With the headmaster the - he was - affectionately k}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 
nown as Teddy, Mr Edward Norris}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595  was his name. His study was right
 in the corner of the boys - hall, there was a wooden spiral staircase that went up to his study. Any boy seen to disappear there that meant he was for it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What kind of things would you have to do to warrant that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Truant too many times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was there much truancy in school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No. Severely dealt with. You know how misdemean - misdemeanours happen. And it'd be cured - ignorant of some children not realizing the - how severe it was. But - if it was really naughty - whether it was act of bad tem
per or anything else, it was dealt with. Across the palm of the hand. Or if there was any show of temper, trousers down and you - were walloped. I once had that experience of having the cane. I felt humiliated by it. I never went up there again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What did you do for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
I can't remember what I done but I remember going up there. 'Cos after all, until you're found out you - you're inclined to be - show - acts of bravado, show off in front of your friends could be over something and which is - pro
bably somebody else would suffer and you're doing something wrong. Could be in that - atmosphere. But on the whole - now I'll tell you another thing too, as you know with school - ground floor was infants - first floor was boys school - top floor was for 
-
 second floor, girls school. At the end of one corridor was the stairway of the girls, but that was strictly out of bounds. No boy would ever dream of walking down - they had to sort of - wait 'til the girls had - even - the - part - high partition wall -
 in the playground, girls were playing over there but - wouldn't dream of - of interrupting any privacy there. That's strict.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were the children all from the same kind of homes as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, all - see otherwise they would go - high class scho
ol would either go down to the High Street Marylebone to - High - they call that Central School. Otherwise it was working class elementary. You went there at five and as you see, put your - years 'til you were fourteen and then you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You say there were some boys who didn't have shoes and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were they sort of looked down upon at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No, it was accepted somehow. There's no doubt parents would - criticize them amongst themselves. Criticize the parents but somehow i
t was accepted. In fact, if you had boots and shoes you'd want to be like him, you'd want to throw your shoes and socks off sort of thing. Not knowing before that it was - compulsory. And of course the great friend of - the poor in those days, there was P
o
or Relief you know, there was such a thing as that. Every Monday there was a - a kitchen in St Johns Wood where you could get pease pudding, faggots, and also too - there was always that regular visit to the pawn broker. Monday to Wednesday they'd pawn th
ings for ready money, and if the wage earner came in Friday or Saturday with money then they would redeem and wear those clothes on the Sunday. And to some that was a practice - a regular practice. Pawnbroker got his living.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Do you remember any children being sort of left out of things at all at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No. No. No. There was none of that. Only by their own - lazy attitudes, you know. But - not for - any spite or anything like that, no, everybody was in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did the teachers always treat everybody the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Yes. No, same treatment was given to all - there was probably a little bit of favouritism, but not a lot.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did anybody in your family ever have anything to do with the Parish people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. None at all. None at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Do you remember feeling when you were young that your parents had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No, somehow because I suppose they were always - their main thought was for us two boys. That's the only thing I can look at. I'm sure mother must have denied 
herself quite a bit 'cos - I knew - on a - knowing the value that - that - the periods of unemployment with dad. So that as he - he - should have been the main wage earner, he just didn't earn. And of course unemployment was nothing was it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was there unemployment benefit he could get?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
I think in a small way but not a - not a lot. Even then they were always up for a means test. Those were the days too if you were unemployed you signed on three times a week. And - went cap in hand down there too. Oh yes, that prevailed then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Can you remember whether there were any newspapers around the house and books and magazines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. Just the one newspaper which was our - News Chronicle, and always the News of the World Sundays. We'd buy our comics - a
nd I'd buy my school - papers. School books like the penny popular, the Gem, the Magnet, the Boyfriend. Used to love - to read about school life, especially if there was any sport going, I used to love it. But otherwise magazines no. Tit-Bits. If you're g
oing into any sort of weekly, occasionally mother would buy Tit-Bits. That's all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did they ever read to you, or read amongst themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No. No, they wasn't that way minded. Because I was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did they tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Well - no doub
t in the early days they told me stories, but - when I was able I always had to be in an open space, I had to be out, I had to play. I was a fidget, as soon as I had me meals I'd want to be out. So therefore was - no, I was not -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you play with your brother very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. In the early days. Always be sport.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 He was interested in sport as well was he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes, Bill was a good sportsman. Football, cricket.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Can you remember whether you were allowed to take books or toys to the table when you were eating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. That was bad manners. And that was never - well it was just discouraged. Put that down.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were you taught to hold your knife and fork in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Never any elbow on - on the table. Sit there - sit there o
rderly, oh most strict in that respect there. Don't make a noise when you're eating, and so on. But just told of it, not - you know, not cuffed in any way. I suppose the fact that we - just took notice of what was told to us. Oh yes, there was always that
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you have set places at table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Yes. I had my chair against the wall and as you know I told you about how I'd hide my fireworks, approaching Guy Fawkes Day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about things like when you wanted the salt or something on the table, could you ask for it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Or did you just take it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. You'd respectfully say, will you pass - always a please. If not you were picked up about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Could you get down when you felt like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. I'd want to get down, no, you sit there. Sit there and that's the end of it. 'Cos the next second you'd be worrying to get up again.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Were you allowed to ask for second helpings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, no, no, mother would stick rigid to that, just the - that one - what she - supplied, that - that
 would be sufficient. That's how - I should imagine that mother - had a method in her mind the same way as she accumulated that little bit of money and so on.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 What about things that were left uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You were told about that. But I don't know any - no, we were healthy people, healthy appetites.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 When you had breakfast would all the family be there or would your mother be out at work by then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. I would be - be there with mother, dad probably if he was working - would be 
out. Mostly an egg for breakfast. Wintertime porridge. Quaker Oats.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Then you'd make do at midday, you wouldn't come home to midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 If - if we came home, there'd be - sandwich of something. And probably have a good high tea when we - but of
 course the weekend naturally there was a good knife and fork lunch. Weekends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Then you had a joint of something on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. That's how we - carried on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did your mother ever make her own jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No. None of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Or pickles or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. I was -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Could you talk during meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No. Although you did, but you were picked up. Mum and dad would converse. And it'd be a case of we - we were eager to interrupt you were told, now look, be quiet, just be have yoursel
f, boys should be seen and not heard. That was always foremost in the - in the first statement.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 How was the meal served up, was it from the table or the stove or what?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, out of the cooking utensils, dished right up and there you are.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Would you have any particular order you were served in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, no, no, probably dad might get it first. Probably, but - no, there wasn't any -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you say grace before meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No, no. Never did. None - none of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Did you have anything like family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
No. No. No, we - we would be - as a part of our education, we would go to Sunday school - we would go to church, the children, not the parents.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Was there anything like a temperance league?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 No. No. No. Band of Hope. We child
ren went to Band of Hope. Because that - we - we would gain an extra treat. There'd be sort of a - a tea party at some time or other or be a treat and so on. That's why you attended so many in those days like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Where did your mother and father come from, you say your father came from St Johns area?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Dad was born in St Johns Wood, mother - was a Marylebone woman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 So they were very local?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 Yes. Considered - St Johns Wood considered in the borough of Marylebone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4738731 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 You say your father was a member of the workingmen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid7303732\charrsid13067595 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 s club, how often would he go there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8675640 ET  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2248743\charrsid13067595 
In the early days every night. See, being a building worker, they finish at five. After his tea he'd wash - mother was content with sitting there and mending, and dad would go to his workingmen}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
